      "message": "The downside of this is that it\u0027s going to produce potentially thousands of errors is the image is wrong.  Here\u0027s a cool helper that can compare a row at a time and output the indices that don\u0027t match:\n\ntesting::AssertionResult RowsMatch(unsigned char* expected,\n                                   unsigned char* actual, size_t rowBytes) {\n    for (size_t i \u003d 0; i \u003c rowBytes; ++i) {\n        if (expected[i] !\u003d actual[i]) {\n            return testing::AssertionFailure() \u003c\u003c \"array[\" \u003c\u003c i \u003c\u003c \"] \"\n                \u003c\u003c \"(\" \u003c\u003c actual[i] \u003c\u003c \") !\u003d expected[\" \u003c\u003c i \u003c\u003c \"] \"\n                \u003c\u003c \"(\" \u003c\u003c expected[i] \u003c\u003c \")\";\n        }\n    }\n\n    return testing::AssertionSuccess();\n}\n\nWith that it can be reduced to one error per row, or even early-out on the first failure if the EXPECT_EQ is changed to ASSERT_EQ:\n\nfor (int i \u003d 0; i \u003c height; i++) {\n    ASSERT_EQ(pixels[(height - i - 1) * width * bpp], pixelsOut[i * width * bpp], width * bpp)\n        \u003c\u003c \"Row mismatch \" \u003c\u003c i;\n}\n\n(Note: Code isn\u0027t guaranteed to compile)",
